    "body_en": "<p>A team using the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope has uncovered a new type of astronomical object —a starless, gas-rich, dark-matter cloud that is considered a “relic” or remnant of early galaxy formation. Nicknamed “Cloud-9,” this is the… The announcement reflects an extended chain of observation, instrumentation, or mission work.</p><p>This matters because cosmology is in an unusually data-rich phase. Precision surveys are no longer merely cataloguing the universe; they are stress-testing the standard model with enough statistical power to expose tensions. The current report adds a concrete element to that larger picture: a team using the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope has uncovered a new type of astronomical object —a starless, gas-rich, dark-matter cloud that is considered a “relic” or….</p><p>The report adds another layer: Nicknamed “Cloud-9,” this is the first confirmed detection of such an object in the Universe. In the same direction, “In science, we usually learn more from the failures than from the successes. In cosmology, a claim only grows up when this level of technical specificity is visible.</p><p>The report adds another layer: Cloud-9 gives us a rare look at a dark-matter-dominated cloud.” The object is called a Reionization-Limited H I Cloud, or &quot;RELHIC.” The term “H I” refers to neutral hydrogen,…. In the same direction, “Before we used Hubble, you could argue that this is a faint dwarf galaxy that we could not see with ground-based telescopes. That kind of precision is what keeps grand conclusions from floating free of the data.</p><p>Another operational detail is this: “But with Hubble’s Advanced Camera for Surveys , we’re able to nail down that there’s nothing there.” The discovery of this relic cloud was a surprise. In the same direction, scientists have been studying hydrogen clouds near the Milky Way for many years, and these clouds tend to be much bigger and irregular than Cloud-9. This is precisely the sort of detail that matters when small systematic effects can mimic deep cosmological implications.</p><p>In more concrete terms, compared with other observed clouds, Cloud-9 is smaller, more compact, and highly spherical, making it look very different from other clouds. In the same direction, but if the pressure of the gas is balancing the gravity of the dark matter cloud, which it appears to be, Cloud-9 must be heavily dominated by dark matter, at about 5…. That kind of precision is what keeps grand conclusions from floating free of the data.</p><p>The significance goes beyond a single dataset because cosmology progresses by consistency checks across independent surveys and inference pipelines. In this case, a team using the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope has uncovered a new type of astronomical object —a starless, gas-rich, dark-matter cloud that is considered a….</p><p>The source base also matters. Because this story comes from ESA Hubble News, it should be read as a primary institutional account of a result, mission update, or analysis pipeline, not as a substitute for later independent scrutiny.</p><p>What matters now is whether the effect remains standing when other surveys, other calibrations, and tighter controls on systematics are brought to bear.</p><p class=\"art-source\"><a href=\"https://esahubble.org/news/heic2601/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Source</a></p>",
