    "body_en": "<p>The new institutional update in Earth science is built around a clear development: every green leaf on Earth does something remarkable, it absorbs visible light for photosynthesis but reflects near-infrared light back into space, creating a distinctive spectral signature that could in principle be spotted from across the…</p><p>To put the story in context, it helps to remember something basic about Earth science: earth science is strongest when local observations can be placed inside longer temporal records and broader physical context. One datapoint is interesting; convergent records are evidence. The current report adds a concrete element to that larger picture: every green leaf on Earth does something remarkable, it absorbs visible light for photosynthesis but reflects near-infrared light back into space, creating a distinctive….</p><p>The article also makes clear that now a new study has tackled one of the biggest obstacles to using it, the messy, patchy reality of real…. In the same direction, now a new study has tackled one of the biggest obstacles to using it, the messy, patchy reality of real planets with real clouds. This is the sort of specificity that lets Earth science scale from an event to a process.</p><p>A further relevant point is that imagine looking at Earth from a distant star system, armed with a powerful telescope capable of capturing its reflected light. In the same direction, but in doing so it draws a sharp line at the boundary between red and near-infrared wavelengths (around 700 nanometres) and reflects near-infrared strongly back into space…. Placed in context, this is how a local measurement begins to support a broader physical reading.</p><p>The article also makes clear that it&#x27;s a spectral fingerprint of photosynthetic life, and it&#x27;s written into Earth&#x27;s light profile for anyone with the instruments to read it. In the same direction, dark red and blue-green indicate regions of high photosynthetic activity in the ocean and on land, respectively Future observatories, particularly NASA&#x27;s planned Habitable…. This is the sort of specificity that lets Earth science scale from an event to a process.</p><p>Another operational detail is this: But detecting the red edge on a distant exoplanet is far more complicated than it sounds, and a new study by researchers at JPL and NASA Goddard Space Flight Center has…. In the same direction, previous models of Earth like exoplanets tended to treat their surfaces and atmospheres as uniform with a single type of terrain and a consistent cloud layer. This is the sort of specificity that lets Earth science scale from an event to a process.</p><p>The significance is strongest when the observation plugs into larger climatic, geophysical, or environmental dynamics. That is why the article deserves to be read as more than a passing update.</p><p>As always, the provenance matters. An institutional source such as Universe Today is valuable because it sits close to the data and operations, but it is still not the endpoint of scientific validation.</p><p>The strongest confirmation will come from placing this result inside longer time series and other independent instruments, reducing the risk of reading too much into a single episode.</p><p class=\"art-source\"><a href=\"https://www.universetoday.com/articles/how-plants-could-betray-themselves-across-the-galaxy\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Source</a></p>",
