    "body_en": "<p>A new analysis of samples from the asteroid Bennu has solved a long-standing mystery: Cracks in the boulders strewn across its surface masquerade as sand. The post NASA Has Cracked the Mystery of Asteroid Bennu’s Boulders appeared first on…</p><p>To put the story in context, it helps to remember something basic about astronomy: astronomy progresses by stacking observations across wavelengths, instruments, and timescales. Any robust result matters because it either tightens or destabilizes the models that were already on the table. The current report adds a concrete element to that larger picture: a new analysis of samples from the asteroid Bennu has solved a long-standing mystery: Cracks in the boulders strewn across its surface masquerade as sand. The post NASA….</p><p>The report adds another layer: The post NASA Has Cracked the Mystery of Asteroid Bennu’s Boulders appeared first on Sky &amp; Telescope. In the same direction, a new analysis of samples from the asteroid Bennu has solved a long-standing mystery: Cracks in the boulders strewn across its surface masquerade as sand. That is the kind of detail that turns a general observation into an astrophysical constraint.</p><p>Another operational detail is this: Explore the universe with Sky &amp; Telescope - your ultimate source for stargazing, celestial events, and the latest astronomy news Ramona White is an astrophysics researcher…. In the same direction, (You can unsubscribe anytime) A new analysis of samples from the asteroid Bennu has solved a long-standing mystery: Cracks in the boulders strewn across its surface…. That is the kind of detail that turns a general observation into an astrophysical constraint.</p><p>Another operational detail is this: NASA’s Origins, Spectral Interpretation, Resource Identification, and Security-Regolith Explorer (OSIRIS-REX) delivered 4.29 ounces of pristine material from the asteroid…. In the same direction, a new study published in Nature Communications reveals the cause of this discrepancy — extensive networks of cracks in the boulders cause them to masquerade as sand. This is where a broad report starts becoming scientifically specific.</p><p>The report adds another layer: In preparation for the OSIRIS-REX mission, the Spitzer Space Telescope observed Bennu in 2007, measuring how quickly the surface heats up and cools down (a property…. In the same direction, the research team first tested the theory that irregular gaps, or pores , would account for some of the heat loss with laser measurements. This is where a broad report starts becoming scientifically specific.</p><p>The broader significance here is not just the object itself, but the way the measurement helps narrow what is still physically plausible. In this case, a new analysis of samples from the asteroid Bennu has solved a long-standing mystery: Cracks in the boulders strewn across its surface masquerade as sand. The post….</p><p>As always, the provenance matters. An institutional source such as Sky &amp; Telescope is valuable because it sits close to the data and operations, but it is still not the endpoint of scientific validation.</p><p>The next decisive test will come from independent observations at other wavelengths or with other instruments, which is how the field usually separates durable results from transient excitement.</p><p class=\"art-source\"><a href=\"https://skyandtelescope.org/astronomy-news/nasa-has-cracked-the-mystery-of-asteroid-bennus-boulders/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Source</a></p>",
